Let (1 \triangleleft \lambda \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) be a representable directed containers and (B \triangleleft \lambda \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \otimes ^B, \text {pr}^B) be a writer monad container. By specialising comonad-monad container distributive laws to these, u_2 and v_2 trivialise and we are left with:
\begin {align*} \alpha \ f\ o^A &= o^A\\ \alpha \ f\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= \alpha \ f\ a \oplus ^A (\alpha \ (\lambda a''. f\ (\alpha \ f\ a \oplus ^A a''))\ a')\\ \alpha \ (\lambda \_ . \iota ^B)\ a &= a\\ \alpha \ (\lambda a' . f\ a' \otimes ^B g\ a')\ a &= \alpha \ f\ (\alpha \ g\ a) \end {align*}
where we take: \alpha \ f\ a := v_1\ \{*\}\ \{f\}\ *\ a

Let (A \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \otimes ^A, \text {pr}^A) be a writer monad container and (1 \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be a representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a monad-comonad container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_1 and v_1 disappear and we are left with:
       \begin {align*}       u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b &= \iota ^A\\       v_2\ \{\iota ^A\}\ b\ * &= b\\       u_2\ (a \otimes ^A a')\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b &= u_2\ a\ b \otimes ^A (u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ (v_2\ \{a\}\ b\ *))\\       v_2\ (a \otimes ^A a')\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b &= v_2\ a\ (v_2\ a'\ b)\\       u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ o^B &= a\\       v_2\ \{a\}\ o^B\ * &= o^B\\       u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ (b \oplus ^B b') &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b')\ b\\       v_2\ \{a\}\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ * &= (v_2\ \{u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b'\}\ b\ *) \oplus ^B (v_2\ \{a\}\ b'\ *)     \end {align*}   
  which (up to ignoring trivial arguments) exhibit u_2 and v_2 as a matching pair of monoid maps between the monoids (A , \iota ^A, \otimes ^A) and (B, o^B, \oplus ^B).

In monad container language: (S \triangleleft P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) satisfies the "disjoint substitution condition" if for all shapes s, s_0 : S, positions p : P\ s, functions f : P\ s \to S where f\ p = \iota , and functions g : P\ s \to S where:
\begin {align*} g\ p &:= s_0\\ g\ p' &:= \iota \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text {if } p' \neq p \end {align*}
then we have: \sigma \ (\sigma \ s\ g)\ (f \circ \text {pr}_1) = \sigma \ (\sigma \ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}_1)

(S \triangleleft  P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) satisfies absorbtion (TODO: not a good name!) if there exist an s : S, and f : P\ s \to  S such that for any p : P\ s we have:
           \sigma \ s\ f^{p} = \iota      
    using the shorthand:
           f^p := \lambda  p' .        \begin {cases}         \iota  & \text {if } p' = p\\         f\ p' & \text {otherwise}       \end {cases}

Let S \triangleleft  P be a container. A monad container (or mnd-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleleft  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \iota  &: S\\       \sigma  &: \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  S) \to  S\\       \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  S\}} P\ (\sigma \ s\ f) \to  \sum _{p : P\ s} P\ (f\ p)     \end {align*}   
  For which the following laws hold:
       \begin {align*}       \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota  ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ \iota \ (\lambda  \_ . a ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ (\sigma \ a\ f)\ (\lambda  p . g\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)) &= \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  p . \sigma \ (f\ p)\ (g\ p))\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)     \end {align*}   
  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \sigma  above them.
